{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514245","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514245"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:20:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12303"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12303"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.67,0.09,0.06,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4823"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78062"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4823"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12303"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63484"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"358"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"1698"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26741"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78062"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department (ED) with a two day history of increasing scrotal pain, nausea, light-headedness and shakes. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is in obvious discomfort. His blood pressure is 98/70 mmHg, pulse 110/min and temperature 38.3C. His BMI is 31. There is widespread discolouration with sharp demarcation over the scrotum (Image). The scrotum is warm and markedly oedematous and even the lightest palpation results in significant pain. Further examination is not practical because of his pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Testicular torsion","Fournier gangrene","Scrotal cellulitis","Epididymitis","Incarcerated inguinoscrotal hernia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is septic and the underlying problem is necrotising fasciitis, originating in the scrotum and otherwise known as \u003Cstrong\u003EFournier gangrene. \u003C/strong\u003ENecrotising fasciitis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis a polymicrobial synergistic infection originating in subcutaneous tissue and the perineum and male genitalia is a common site of origin. The pathophysiological process usually involves the spread along the subcutaneous fascial layers and the immunocompromised or diabetic patients are most prone to this problem. Necrotising fasciitis is a life-threatening condition that requires prompt recognition and intervention. After fluid resuscitation, broad spectrum intravenous antibiotics must be given and surgical debridement done as soon as possible to remove all necrotic tissues and contain the spread of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpididymitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to infection/inflammation of the epididymis which often occurs gradually with lower abdominal or testicular pain being the prominent features. This patient has a far more extensive involvement than just the epididymis with the widespread discolouration and palpable crepitus suggesting a more virulent infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScrotal cellulitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a reasonable differential diagnosis for the patient in the stem above. However, given the evidence of systemic involvement and pictured evidence of necrotic tissue the diagnosis of Fournier gangrene is more appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETesticular torsion\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the twisting of a testicle on the spermatic cord and is linked with strenuous activity or following trauma however there have been cases of it occurring during sleep. It is more common in children and young adults. Symptoms include significant testicular pain and may be associated with nausea and vomiting. The absence of the cremaster reflex is strongly linked with testicular torsion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eincarcerated inguinoscrotal hernia \u003C/strong\u003Eis most likely to result from an indirect inguinal hernia and refers to a hernia which is unable to be reduced. Incarcerated inguinoscrotal hernias may result in bowel obstruction type symptoms and are unlikely to result in overlying necrotic tissue as pictured above.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fournier gangrene should be considered in any patient presenting with testicular/scrotal pain and fever.","Prompt surgical intervention is critical in the management of Fournier gangrene to prevent further tissue necrosis and systemic spread."],"references":["Lewis GD, Majeed M, Olang CA, Patel A, Gorantla VR, Davis N, Gluschitz S. Fournier\u0027s Gangrene Diagnosis and Treatment: A Systematic Review. Cureus. 2021 Oct 21;13(10):e18948. doi: 10.7759/cureus.18948. PMID: 34815897; PMCID: PMC8605831. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34815897/","Montrief T, Long B, Koyfman A, Auerbach J. Fournier Gangrene: A Review for Emergency Clinicians. J Emerg Med. 2019 Oct;57(4):488-500. doi: 10.1016/j.jemermed.2019.06.023. Epub 2019 Aug 28. PMID: 31472943. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31472943/","Singh A, Ahmed K, Aydin A, Khan MS, Dasgupta P. Fournier\u0027s gangrene. A clinical review. Arch Ital Urol Androl. 2016 Oct 5;88(3):157-164. doi: 10.4081/aiua.2016.3.157. PMID: 27711086. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27711086/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12303"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18423"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18423"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0c51329c-2ca2-4198-9f08-2f76c6c02e3e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0c51329c-2ca2-4198-9f08-2f76c6c02e3e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":555,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63484"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T12:36:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T12:36:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4823"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78062"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"at